### Template Classes

Class templates allow defining a generic class that works with any data type.

---

### Basic Class Template

```cpp
template <typename T>
class Box {
private:
  T content;

public:
  void set(const T& value) { content = value; }
  T get() const { return content; }
};
```

---

### Using Template Classes

```cpp
Box<int> intBox;
intBox.set(42);

Box<string> stringBox;
stringBox.set("Hello");

Box<Box<int>> nestedBox;  // Nested template
```

---

### Multiple Template Parameters

```cpp
template <typename Key, typename Value>
class Pair {
public:
  Key first;
  Value second;

  Pair(Key k, Value v) : first(k), second(v) {}
};

Pair<string, int> person("Alice", 30);
```

---

### Template Template Parameters

```cpp
template <typename T, template <typename> class Container>
class Wrapper {
  Container<T> data;
};
```

---

### Class Template Specialization

```cpp
// Primary template
template <typename T>
class Storage { /* ... */ };

// Full specialization for bool
template <>
class Storage<bool> {
  // Optimized implementation for bool
};

// Partial specialization for pointers
template <typename T>
class Storage<T*> {
  // Implementation for any pointer type
};
```

---

> **Key Point:** Class templates must have all template arguments specified when instantiating (unlike function templates where deduction occurs). Member functions defined outside the class need the template parameter again.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

template <typename T>
class Calculator {
public:
  T add(T a, T b) { return a + b; }
  T multiply(T a, T b) { return a * b; }
};

int main() {
  Calculator<int> intCalc;
  cout << "Int: " << intCalc.add(5, 3) << endl;

  Calculator<double> doubleCalc;
  cout << "Double: " << doubleCalc.add(2.5, 1.5) << endl;
  return 0;
}
